<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08076a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08076a">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08076a"> 76(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> as madmen tongue &amp; / brain not</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">As a great many native nouns and verbs had thus come to be identical in form &hellip;, it was quite natural that the speech-instinct should take it as a matter of course that whenever the need of a verb arose, the corresponding noun might be used unchanged, and vice versa. &hellip; Nearly every word for the different parts of the body has given rise to a homonym verb &hellip; <i>tongue</i>, <i>brain</i>, (such stuffe <b>as madmen tongue and braine not</b>; Shakesp. Cymbeline) <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 161-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
